title: [XLA:SPMD] Optimize the partitioning for element-wise operations when all operands share the same sharding.
body:
[XLA:SPMD] Optimize the partitioning for element-wise operations when all operands share the same sharding.

Let us take `C with S3 = add(A with S1, B with S2)` as an example, where `A, B, C` are tensors, `S1, S2, S3` are their shardings.

Before this change, we always have
```
A with S3 = reshard(A with S1, new_sharding=S3)
B with S3 = reshard(B with S2, new_sharding=S3)
C with S3 = add(A with S3, B with S3)
```

With this cl, if S1 and S2 are the same, we will have
```
C with S1 = add(A with S1, B with S1)
C with S3 = reshard(C with S1)
```
The new partitioning method can reduce the number of reshards.
author: copybara-service[bot]

title: [XLA] Created new AlgebraicSimplifierOptions field for separately controlling rewrites previously all controlled by use_associative_reordering.
body:
[XLA] Created new AlgebraicSimplifierOptions field for separately controlling rewrites previously all controlled by use_associative_reordering.

use_associative_reordering is responsible for:
- dot(dot(a, b), c) to dot(a, dot(b, c))
- dot(pad(a), b) to dot(a, slice(b)) and similar for broadcast/reduce and reverse/reverse

raise_slice_and_reduce_through_dot is responsible for:
- slice(dot(a, b)) to dot(slice(a), slice(b))
- reduce(dot(a, b)) to dot(reduce(a), reduce(b))
author: copybara-service[bot]

body:
PR #14699: Add while-loop-trip-count-annotator before collective-permute-valid-iteration-annotator pass

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/14699

While loop trip count was not annotated to the while instruction, which meant that the collective-permute-valid-iteration-annotator could not deduce the valid iterations for collective-permute
Copybara import of the project:

--
26f12d1e7c504cab0ca876e3685c49b98060b816 by Shraiysh Vaishay <svaishay@nvidia.com>:

Add while-loop-trip-count-annotator before collective-permute-valid-iteration-annotator pass

While loop trip count was not annotated to the while instruction, which meant that the collective-permute-valid-iteration-annotator could not deduce the valid iterations for collective-permute

Merging this change closes #14699

title: [xla:cpu] Replace memcpy with bit_cast in runtime TopK
body:
[xla:cpu] Replace memcpy with bit_cast in runtime TopK

This allows the lambda to be constexpr as bit_cast does basically the same work here, except it provides constexpr benefits. Also, the convert_to_int is static now which omits the need for capturing it in the partial_sort comparison.

Benchmark results ranged from about equal to about -5% depending on a scenario. Negative values denoted time saved/improvement.

title: [tsl:concurrency] Remove AsyncValueRef constructor from immediate value
body:
[tsl:concurrency] Remove AsyncValueRef constructor from immediate value

AsyncValueRef<T> is a reference-counted wrapper around the pointer of type `T`, and has a semantics very similar to std::shared_ptr<T>, with extra async features on top of basic reference counting. Delete implicit constructor that converts values of type `T` into AsyncValueRef<T> wrappers to be more consistent with "smart pointer" semantics.

title: PR #13425: [ROCM] gemm precision settings for autotuner
body:
PR #13425: [ROCM] gemm precision settings for autotuner

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/openxla/xla/pull/13425

Here we add a new flag **xla_gpu_autotune_gemm_rtol** which controls the relative precision used by the BufferComparator (defaults to **0.1**).

Also I added one more "paranoid" level 5 for **xla_gpu_autotune_level** which forces the autotuner to discard solutions with accuracy problems. Long time I was under impression that the autotuner already does it, however this is not the case as outlined [here](https://github.com/ROCm/xla/blob/6301f04c50c7637a65b3e0c6f40be628aa00947f/xla/service/gpu/stream_executor_util.cc#L640). BufferComparator just prints out the error message but **keeps wrong solutions** as possible candidates which could lead to a great confusion. So, the autotune level 5 is supposed to discard solutions with accuracy problems.

Besides, I also did some small refactoring on BufferComparator to simplify the source code and added **verbose** flag in order to mute error messages if needed.

@xla-rotation: could you please have a look?
Copybara import of the project:

--
cab53b672f9546fe4b811d09cf998b105dc8be01 by Pavel Emeliyanenko <pavel.emeliyanenko@amd.com>:

added precision settings for autotuner and buffer_comparator small refactoring, added verbose flag

Merging this change closes #13425
